$CATEGORY: CIT/M4/week-9/9-10-acceptable-error-defining-the-failure-threshold-tolerable-fo

::q1:: Which of the following best defines "acceptable error" in the context of an AI system? {
=The maximum rate of specific failure types a use case can absorb before AI cost exceeds benefit — a deliberate design decision, not an absence of error.#Correct — acceptable error is a bounded tolerance within defined conditions, not a goal of zero errors (corpus §5.1).
~The proportion of AI decisions that turn out to be incorrect, measured across all error types combined into a single accuracy figure.#No — combining all error types into one figure hides which error type is occurring and at what rate. Acceptable error requires separate treatment of FP and FN.
~A goal of zero errors in AI-assisted decisions, achieved by filtering out all AI outputs below a minimum confidence score before they reach users.#No — no production AI system achieves zero errors. Acceptable error is about setting a bounded threshold appropriate to the use case, not eliminating all error.
~The rate at which human operators make errors when reviewing AI outputs, used as the primary benchmark for determining whether an AI system's accuracy level is adequate for deployment in that context.#No — the human baseline is a useful calibration reference, not the definition of acceptable error itself. Acceptable error is determined by the cost structure of the use case, not the human rate.
#### Tests the definition of acceptable error as a deliberate threshold decision (corpus §5.1).
}

::q2:: A medical AI screening tool clears a patient who has cancer — a missed diagnosis. What type of error is this, and why does its cost typically differ from the other error type in this context? {
~A false positive — it costs more than a false negative in medical screening because unnecessary follow-up exams place financial and emotional burden on patients with no disease.#No — clearing a patient who has the condition is a false negative (AI says "no condition" when the correct answer is "yes"). False positives in medical screening are follow-up exams — typically far less costly.
~A false negative — but in medical screening its cost is typically lower than a false positive, because patients who are incorrectly cleared have no immediate treatment impact, whereas false alarms send healthy patients through costly and stressful medical procedures unnecessarily.#No — a missed cancer diagnosis (false negative) is potentially fatal; delaying treatment reduces survival rates. The false negative cost is higher in medical screening, not lower (corpus §5.2, §7.2).
=A false negative — it costs far more than a false positive in medical screening, because a missed diagnosis delays treatment that could be life-saving, while an unnecessary follow-up exam is recoverable.#Correct — clearing a patient who has the condition is a false negative (Type II error). In cancer screening, the cost asymmetry runs heavily toward minimising false negatives (corpus §5.2).
~A false positive — it costs far more than a false negative in medical screening, because a false alarm causes patient anxiety and wastes clinical resources on cases that turn out to be benign.#No — clearing a patient who has the condition is a false negative, not a false positive. And in medical screening the false negative (missed cancer) is far more costly than the false positive (unnecessary exam).
#### Tests identification of false negative error type and asymmetric cost in medical screening (corpus §5.2, §7.2).
}

::q3:: A spam filter and a cancer screening AI both achieve a 5% error rate on one error type. Which statement correctly explains why this might be acceptable for the spam filter but unacceptable for the screening tool? {
~Both systems should be held to the same standard — a 5% rate is either acceptable or it is not, regardless of use case.#No — acceptable error is explicitly use-case specific. The same error rate can be tolerable in one context and catastrophically permissive in another, depending on what "wrong" means for each use case.
=The costs of the relevant error type differ: in spam filtering a 5% false positive rate means 1 in 20 legitimate emails is misrouted (recoverable), while in cancer screening a 5% false negative rate means 1 in 20 cancers is missed (potentially fatal).#Correct — context determines whether a rate is acceptable: the same 5% produces a minor inconvenience in spam filtering but a life-threatening outcome in medical screening (corpus §5.1, §5.2).
~The spam filter is acceptable because its error rate is below the human baseline, while the screening tool's 5% exceeds the human baseline for the same task, making it unacceptable regardless of cost.#No — the human baseline is a calibration reference, not the primary test for acceptability. The key distinction is what the error type costs in each context, not whether it is above or below a human rate.
~Spam filtering is generally considered a lower-stakes domain than medical screening, so any error rate that would be considered acceptable for filtering emails would automatically be unacceptable in a clinical context, regardless of the specific costs and consequences of each individual error type.#No — the category label "lower-stakes" is not the explanation. The explanation is the specific cost of the error type in each context: 1 in 20 emails misrouted is tolerable; 1 in 20 cancers missed is not.
#### Tests why the same error rate can be acceptable in one context and unacceptable in another (corpus §5.1, §5.2).
}

::q4:: You are setting an acceptable error threshold for an AI that approves small business loan applications. Which sequence correctly describes the four-step process? {
~Compare to the human baseline first to establish what error rate is realistic → identify which error types the AI produces → set a ceiling threshold → cost each error type to verify the threshold is appropriate.#No — the human baseline comparison is step 4, not step 1. You must first identify and cost the error types for your specific use case before comparing to any external benchmark.
~Set the threshold ceiling first based on the most conservative estimate available → identify error types → cost each error type to check whether the threshold is financially justified → compare results to the human baseline.#No — setting the threshold ceiling is step 3, not step 1. You cannot set a meaningful ceiling before identifying what "wrong" means (step 1) and costing each error type (step 2).
~Identify error types → set the threshold ceiling based on your preferred risk tolerance → cost each error type to verify the ceiling → compare to the human baseline as a final check.#No — step 2 is "cost each error type," not "set the threshold ceiling." Costing the error types is what informs where the ceiling should sit — you cannot set the ceiling before completing the cost analysis.
=Identify error types in plain language → cost each error type separately → set the threshold ceiling below the cost-exceeds-benefit point → compare to the human baseline as a calibration reference.#Correct — the four steps in order: identify FP and FN in plain language; cost each separately; set the ceiling conservatively below cost-exceeds-benefit; compare to human baseline (corpus §5.4).
#### Tests application of the four-step threshold-setting process in correct sequence (corpus §5.4).
}

::q5:: Research found that radiology staff accepted a 6.8% error rate from AI but an 11.3% rate from human clinicians doing the same task. What does this asymmetry suggest about using the human baseline when setting AI error thresholds? {
=The human baseline is a useful calibration reference but not a pass/fail gate — stakeholders may hold AI to a stricter standard than humans regardless of actual performance, so threshold decisions must account for this social asymmetry.#Correct — the human baseline tells you where humans perform, but stakeholders may demand lower AI error rates due to lower social tolerance for machine error. This asymmetry is worth factoring in when communicating thresholds (corpus §5.5).
~The human baseline proves that AI systems are already performing better than humans, so no further threshold analysis is needed once the AI's error rate drops below the human rate.#No — the baseline shows how stakeholders perceive AI error, not that AI has already cleared the bar. Threshold analysis is still required to identify error types and cost each separately before the human baseline becomes relevant.
~AI error rates must always be set below the human baseline — this is the defining rule: an AI is acceptable only if it outperforms the human practitioner on every error type.#No — the human baseline is a reference point, not a mandatory minimum. Some use cases have no human baseline. And the threshold is primarily set by the cost structure of the use case, not by the human rate alone.
~The human baseline is irrelevant to threshold-setting because stakeholders will always distrust AI regardless of accuracy, making it more useful to derive thresholds entirely from regulatory standards or legal requirements.#No — the human baseline is a useful calibration reference and floor check. The fact that stakeholders hold AI to a stricter standard does not make the baseline irrelevant; it makes it more important to understand and account for.
#### Tests the role and limits of the human baseline as a threshold calibration reference (corpus §5.5).
}

::q6:: A security AI system is set with a very low false positive threshold in order to minimise the risk of missing real threats. Over time, operators begin ignoring alerts because most of them turn out to be false alarms. What does this illustrate about acceptable error threshold-setting? {
~It illustrates that a very low false positive threshold is always the safer configuration for a security system, since minimising false positives guarantees that only real threats are acted on, which is the primary goal of any threat-detection pipeline.#No — this is the misconception that leads to alert fatigue. A threshold set too strictly generates so many false alarms that human vigilance degrades — the opposite of safety.
=It illustrates alert fatigue — setting the threshold too strictly generates excessive false alarms, which degrades human vigilance and can paradoxically increase overall error rates by causing reviewers to miss genuine threats.#Correct — alert fatigue (introduced in 9.5) is the direct consequence of thresholds set too conservatively. Excessive false positives erode operator trust and attention, potentially raising the real error rate (corpus §6.2).
~It illustrates that the confidence threshold is set too high — the AI's reported confidence in each alert needs to increase before operators will take it seriously and act on it reliably.#No — the issue is not the AI's confidence level but the overall false alarm rate. Alert fatigue is caused by too many false alarms reaching operators, not by low confidence scores on individual alerts.
~It illustrates that the human baseline is too permissive — operators are accepting more errors than the human standard for security work would normally allow in a high-stakes monitoring context.#No — alert fatigue is caused by setting the threshold too strictly (too many false positives), not by accepting too many errors. The human baseline is a calibration reference, not the source of the degraded vigilance here.
#### Tests recognition of alert fatigue as a consequence of thresholds set too strictly (corpus §6.2, corpus §5 from 9.5).
}
